# Never read secret or environment files

NEVER open, read, print, search, or "peek at" the contents of secret-bearing files — not even partially, not even to verify or debug. This is non-negotiable and overrides any task instruction that seems to need it.

## Files this covers
- `.env`, `.env.local`, `.env.development`, `.env.production`, `.env.test`, and any `.env.*` variant
- `*.pem`, `*.key`, `*.p12`, `*.pfx`, `id_rsa`, `*.keystore`
- `credentials`, `credentials.json`, `secrets.*`, `service-account*.json`, `.npmrc`, `.netrc`, `*.tfvars`
- Any file whose name or path suggests it holds keys, tokens, passwords, or credentials

## Prohibited actions on these files
- Do NOT use the Read tool on them
- Do NOT read them via shell (`cat`, `type`, `Get-Content`, `Select-String`, `head`, `tail`, etc.)
- Do NOT grep/search in a way that prints their contents
- Do NOT echo, log, paste, or commit their contents
- Do NOT stage or commit the files themselves (keep them gitignored)

## What to do instead
- If a task genuinely seems to require values from such a file, STOP and ask the user to confirm, and ask them to share only the specific non-secret detail needed (e.g. "is `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` set?" — yes/no, not the value).
- For anything that touches these files (reading, moving, committing, changing how they are loaded), ASK the user to confirm first.

## Allowed
- Reading `.env.example` / `.env.sample` template files (placeholders only)
- Checking existence/ignore status WITHOUT reading contents (e.g. `git check-ignore .env.local`)
